  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3056263924" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3056263924" />
    <a title="Tim Casteel" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/53304148-tim-casteel"><img alt="Tim Casteel" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1546489294p2/53304148.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3056263924?book_show_action=true">Nov 20, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Tim Casteel" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Tim Casteel" href="/user/show/53304148-tim-casteel">Tim Casteel</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3056263924" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer9213746424879188642">Though written in 1987, perfectly applicable to the world/college campus today. I found the book to be uneven, quite challenging, but brilliant. A bit of a slog in parts but aside from one bizarre rant on 80&apos;s Hair Metal, most of the content was fascinating. <br/><br/>Bloom attempts no small feat: &quot;I have tried to provide the outline of an archeology of our souls as they are.&quot; To dig down into the past to understand how we got to now.<br/>And to set forth, for the university in particular, a clarion call:<br/>&quot;The </span>
  <span id="freeText9213746424879188642" style="display:none">Though written in 1987, perfectly applicable to the world/college campus today. I found the book to be uneven, quite challenging, but brilliant. A bit of a slog in parts but aside from one bizarre rant on 80's Hair Metal, most of the content was fascinating. <br /><br />Bloom attempts no small feat: "I have tried to provide the outline of an archeology of our souls as they are." To dig down into the past to understand how we got to now.<br />And to set forth, for the university in particular, a clarion call:<br />"The university's task is thus well defined: always to maintain the permanent questions front and center. This it does primarily by preserving — by keeping alive — the works of those who best addressed these questions."<br /><br />'Closing' is a shaft of light, leading us down into a mineshaft of diamonds: "There is a lifetime and more of study here, which would turn our impoverishing certitudes into humanizing doubts."<br />His call is to lay aside our shallow modern certainty and plunge into the depths of the great thinkers and books that asked the "permanent questions" of life: why am I here, who am I?<br /><br />"We are like ignorant shepherds living on a site where great civilizations once flourished…We need history, not to tell us what happened, or to explain the past, but to make the past alive so that it can explain us and make a future possible."<br /><br />I hope to one day have 1/100th the breadth of knowledge of Dr. Bloom. Incredibly helpful for understanding who are the key influencers that shape our current intellectual and cultural landscape. Modern Americans are "singing a song they do not understand, translated from a German original and… behind it all, the master lyricists are Nietzsche and Heidegger. <br /><br />A few brilliant quotes:<br />"On the way, the goal of happiness was exchanged for the pursuit of safety and comfort…[leaving] a being who no longer knows what he is, who is so absorbed with existing that he has forgotten his reason for existing, who in the event of actually attaining full security and perfect comfort has no notion of what to do."<br /><br />"Nietzsche's new beginning in philosophy starts from the observation that a shared sense of the sacred is the surest way to recognize a culture, and the key to understanding it. <br />What a people bows before tells us what it is."<br /><br />College students come to campus looking for answers not seeking the right questions:<br />"Socratic dialectic always culminates in doubt. Socrates' last word was that he knew that he knew nothing.<br /><br />Man is not just a problem-solving being, as behaviorists would wish us to believe, but a problem-recognizing and -accepting being.<br /><br />[we seek to] solve problems that God and nature had previously seemed to make insoluble, and earlier men had made a virtue of living with. Man has always had to come to terms with God, love and death. They made it impossible to be perfectly at home on earth. But America is coming to terms with them in new ways."</span>
  <a data-text-id="9213746424879188642" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


